<DOC><DOCNO> AP900914-0180 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-09-14-90 1841EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-14 0353</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0416</SECOND><HEAD>Violent Weather Hits the Great Lakes Region; Nebraska Cools Down</HEAD><HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD><TEXT>   Violent weather, heavy rains, and hail pelted parts of Michiganand Indiana and a three-week heat wave in Nebraska broke Friday.   Tornadoes touched down in southern Michigan but there were noreports of injuries. A employee of a dry cleaners in the Detroitsuburb of Beverly Hills said she was sure it was a tornado thatalmost carried her off as it blasted through the building.   ``The wind did pick me up. My feet actually came off the ground.It was pretty scary,'' said Brenda Reeves. ``God was looking outfor me, because if the dry cleaner hadn't come back and grabbed me,I would have gone out of the door.''   There were reports of damage from thunderstorm wind gusts nearChase, Beal City, Paw Paw, Flint, and north of Mishawaka, Ind.Gusts reached 60 mph west of Flint and 65 mph at Crawfordsville,Ind.   Hail hit Tuscola, Mich., and heavy rain from strong stormscaused flooding of streets, small streams and low lying areasaround Three Rivers, Mich.   The sizzling heat wave that had gripped Nebraska since Aug. 23broke Friday with temperatures dropping back into the seasonable80's.   The high in Omaha had averaged 92.5 degrees during the spell,said John Zapotocny, assistant professor of atmospheric sciences atCreighton University. At midday there were showers andthunderstorms over parts of Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky,Ohio and Michigan.   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from North Carolinaacross South Carolina, Georgia, northwest Florida, Alabama,Tennessee, Mississippi, southeast Arkansas, Louisiana, parts ofTexas and southeast New Mexico.   Storms and showers also reached from the North Carolina coastacross eastern Virginia, Delaware, eastern Maryland, southeastPennsylvania and southern New Jersey.   There were scattered showers in central Maine, and southeastFlorida, and rain moved onto the northern coast of Oregon.   Heavier rainfall Friday included 2.71 inches at Oscoda, Mich.,1.35 inches at Grand Rapids, Mich., 1.25 inches at Dover, Del.,1.09 inches at Houghton Lake, Mich., and 1 inch at Millville, N.J.   Low temperature for the Lower 48 states Friday morning was 29degrees at Truckee, Calif., West Yellowstone, Mont., and Burgess,Ind. The Big Horn Mountains of Wyoming reached 22 degrees.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47 atMarquette, Mich., to 101 at Needles, Calif.</TEXT></DOC>